sentences.sentence: Beijing's publication of its own summary of the ice-breaking meeting between China's Foreign Minister, Wang Yi, and Australian counterpart Penny Wong in Bali is an unusual diplomatic manoeuvre.
The benign interpretation is that this is another olive branch being proffered by Beijing, which seeks to use the election of the Albanese government to reset the bilateral relationship.
Mr Wang listed four demands to improve ties: not treating China as an enemy; not doing the US's bidding; seeking common ground; and mutual efforts to improve public opinion.
This amounts to progress, of sorts, compared with that infamous, peak wolf-warrior diplomatic incident, which was the list of 14 grievances issued by the Chinese embassy in 2020.
Yet the tone of Beijing's message - along with the presumed right to issue one-sided diktats demanding Australia take "concrete action" to correct its attitude - remains much the same.
All the blame for the problems in the relationship are placed at Australia's feet.

This, of course, ignores the reality that assertive China has changed.All this is underlined by the attempt to pin the "root cause" of the deteriorating relationship on the former Coalition government's "irresponsible words and deeds" - such as Malcolm Turnbull's legitimate decision to protect Australia's sovereignty by banning China-owned Huawei from participating in the 5G network build.
A closed, one-party state - that would never allow a foreign company near China's critical technologies - expects one-sided reciprocity and openness from Australia.
China would also reject out of hand any similar attempt by another country to meddle in its domestic politics and foreign policy as a precondition for better relations.

If China genuinely seeks a reset of the relationship, it should take the first concrete action itself and withdraw the unwarranted trade punishment against Australia's grain, beef, and wine exports - not make this conditional on improved political relations on its terms first.It's still a welcome step - after the three-year diplomatic deep-freeze initiated by Beijing - that high-level ministerial talks between Australia and China have resumed.
Yet the Albanese government shows no signs of being a soft touch under Beijing's one-way pressure.
Ms Wong reportedly told Mr Wang that while Australia's government had changed, its national interests and policy settings had not.
That was reinforced by Anthony Albanese's statement on Monday that "Australia doesn't respond to demands".

The reality, moreover, is that it is not what China says, but how it acts, that is shaping the government's early foreign policy forays.Hence Mr Albanese this week will make his fourth overseas trip since taking office two months ago to attend the Pacific Island Forum in Fiji, where he will step up the government's efforts to counter China's geostrategic assertiveness in the South Pacific.
Mr Albanese will call on forum member countries to agree to seek security assistance from the regional grouping, rather than through bilateral agreements with non-regional powers.

The aim here is to shore up the region against a repeat of the China-Solomon Islands security pact and is a belated response to Beijing's failed attempt to strike a region-wide, 10-country security deal.The Albanese government may not buy Beijing's line that the Coalition is to blame for the state of the relationship.
But it is playing the blame game by fingering the Morrison government for allegedly failing to engage with the region and for neglecting Australia's security interests in the South Pacific.

To be fair to the former government, the pandemic disruptions dislocated normal diplomacy for two years, and the AUKUS nuclear submarine deal and the rebirth and deepening of the Quad dominated its security agenda.
To be blunt, though, the government was also weighed down by a largely passive, invisible and ineffective foreign minister in Marise Payne.
The energy and expertise that Senator Wong has brought to her new job is a big positive.
Especially when the foreign minister has focused her attention and efforts on back-filling the diplomatic and security hole in Australia's South Pacific backyard that China has exposed.
